title: For Sale:  8" Rifle Solvent Trap (that can be modified to become a) Suppressor or Silencer (legally see description) Aluminum
location: West Des Moines, Des Moines, Iowa
postcontent: You are purchasing a 8" Aluminum Solvent Trap.This solvent trap can be legally modified to become a Form 1 Suppressor for a (small) fraction of the cost of premanufactured suppressors.Set comes with:-1 End threaded for an .223/5.56 barrel (AR-15 or similar) though I can get others for pistols, or larger threads for other rifles, these are just what I have in stock for now. -1 Spacer-9 Cone cups with center marked (will need to be drilled out with a drill press to allow bullet to pass through)-1 End cap with center marked (will need to be drilled out with a drill press to allow bullet to pass through)---WHY YOU SHOULD SUPPRESS YOUR FIREARM---HEARING PROTECTION Suppressors reduce the noise of a gunshot by an average of 20 – 35 dB, which is roughly the same as earplugs or earmuffs. By decreasing the overall sound signature, suppressors help to preserve the hearing of recreational shooters, hunters, and hunting dogs around the world. SAFER HUNTING Most hunters do not wear hearing protection in the field because they want to hear their surroundings. The trouble is, exposure to even a single unsuppressed gunshot can, and often does, lead to permanent hearing damage. Suppressors allow hunters to maintain full situational awareness, while still protecting their hearing. The result is a safer hunting experience for the hunter, and for those nearby. NOISE COMPLAINTS As urban developments advance into rural areas, shooting ranges and hunting preserves across the country are being closed due to noise complaints. ACCURACY One of the most common problems for shooters is decreased accuracy caused by flinching in anticipation of the firearms discharge and recoil. By containing the explosion of the gunpowder at the muzzle, suppressors reduce recoil, and help decrease muzzle flinch. These benefits lead to improved accuracy, better shot placement, and more humane hunts.---HOW IT WORKS---1. Purchase the legal Solvent Trap that attaches to the end of your barrel of your rifle or pistol. 2. Complete the Form 1 tax form and send the $200 tax to the ATF (https://johnpierceesq.com/the-complete-guide-to-the-new-form-1/) 3. Wait until you get your Form 1 Tax Stamp Approval back from the ATF (Last I was told about 100 days) 4. ONLY ONCE APPROVED - You can now modify and drill out the cone cups and the end cap to allow projectile to pass through the Solvent Trap (now legally a suppressor) 5. Go shoot and notice the difference in sound! *It should be noted that Trump has vowed to remove Suppressors from this list that requires the $200 tax stamp fee, once that is done buying a suppressor will be like buying a shotgun - No tax.

title: For Sale:  Civil War Lorenz Rifle
location: West Las Vegas, Las Vegas, Nevada
postcontent: Austrian Lorenz 1854 Rifle Musket. This one saw service in our Civil War, and is in antique good condition. Over 300,000 were acquired by the North and South, second in quantity only to the British Enfield. While some were issued in the original .54 caliber,this one was rebored to @ .58 Cal.  The wood is beechwood. The iron mounts are generally smooth. The bolster, rear of breech and forward part of the lock plate show typical evidence of firing with corrosion from the percussion caps. The date “860” is visible on the lock - the Austrians used only the last three digits of the year, indicating the gun was made in 1860. Front sight is in place as is the original ramrod.  Example of a typical Civil War infantry arm acquired for both Southern and Northern Units in lieu of Springfields and Enfields. Many were acquired early in the War for to arm infantry regiments being organized by the Northern states (my ancestor reportedly carried one in the 3rd Mass Infantry, 1862-63).  Southern use included the Army of Western Tennessee, VMI, et al.

title: For Sale:  Yugo SKS 7.62 x 39 EXCELLENT CONDITION M59/66
postcontent: This is a Graded Excellent Yugoslavian M59/66 SKS in 7.62x39mm caliber. This is a beautiful gun and has been officially graded excellent by gun pros. There is absolutely no rust at all on this gun. It was either in a very lightly used condition or the arsenal did a great job of refinishing the gun. It had a very light coating of cosmolene unlike others that I've had that look like they been immersed in a bath of vaseline. The stock is absulutely beautiful to be 60+ years old. There are no "battle scars" on this metal or stock and only has some light discoloration near the butt of the gun. The bore is very clean and very shiny and looks to have great rifling left, no pitting at all! This is one of the finest SKS rifles or I would say military rifles that you will find per the condition. There is all matching numbers on the items that have serial #'s. This gun is the M59/66 variant and therefore has the grenade launcher attachment.The history behind this gun from the lot that it was bought in was that is was manufactured by Zastava. The M59/66 was adopted in 1967 through 1972 and was quickly replaced by the AK. After getting their use they were put into storage in Slovenia and stayed there until they were deemed unneccesary and then entered into circulation for import. Can meet in the Lenoir City/ Kingston Area. IT comes with the leather mag ouch, oiler, oil mag pouch, sling, and accesory kit. No trades, No low ball offers!
